Perfect, outstanding, amazing! Match your option choice with these. So if I am using option3, I'll use the once below //3 option dialogue. If I'm using option then I'll use //2 option dialogue. And so on.

To enter your things, I kept it VERY simple. Usually, you'd have to do 
[code=java]
if (c.dialogueAction == 1) {
//DOTHINGS
} else if (c.dialogueAction == 2) {
//DOTHINGS
}
[/code]
However, with this, you do
[code=java]
case 1: //If my dialogueAction is 1
//DOTHINGS
break;
case 2: //If my dialogueAction is 2
//DOTHINGS
break;
[/code]
Cool right? It's so much easier and it's less writing for you! Not to mention that it looks more neat too.

[b]But Arham, how do I know if my dialogueAction is what?[/b]

Well, remember, when you were righting in UpdateNPCChat? You wrote:

[code=java]
		case 1:
			dialogueAction = 1;
			options5("Yes", "Kind of", "Probably", "No", "I don't know.");
		break;
[/code]

Here the key: [b]dialogueAction = 1;[/b]
Here's the of this key: [b]= 1;[/b]
And here's the key of this key: [b]1[/b]

Get it?

Now my dialogueAction is 1. I'm now going to implement that. Since I used options5, I'll use the ones below //5 option dialogue.
Here's my code:
[code=java]
		//5 option dialogue:

			//Option 1
		case 8221:
			switch (c.dialogueAction) {
			case 1:
				c.getDiaHandler().dia(1);
			}
		break;

			//Option 2
		case 8222:
			switch (c.dialogueAction) {
			case 1:
				c.getDiaHandler().dia(2);
			}
		break;

			//Option 3
		case 8223:
			switch (c.dialogueAction) {
			case 1:
				c.getDiaHandler().dia(3);
			}
		break;

			//Option 4
		case 8224:
			switch (c.dialogueAction) {
			case 1:
				c.NpcDialogueSend = false;
				c.closeAll();
			}
		break;

			//Option 5
		case 8225:
			switch (c.dialogueAction) {
			case 1:
				c.getDiaHandler().dia(4);
			}
		break;
[/code]

Notice how simple it is? Well, we're done :)

